# UI Boundaries (SUBSYSTEM CONTRACT)

This file defines UI-specific dependency rules on top of the global architecture contract defined in boundaries.mdc.

All global rules still apply.

---

# 1. UI Layer Hierarchy (STRICT)

UI must follow strict layering:

primitives (shadcn/ui)
→ shared/ui
→ features/*
→ layouts/pages

Rule:
- UI layers must only depend downward

---

# 2. Primitives Layer

- Base UI components (shadcn/ui)
- Stateless visual primitives
- Must not depend on application code

Rule:
- primitives are the lowest UI layer

---

# 3. shared/ui Layer

- reusable UI abstractions
- domain-agnostic components
- built only from primitives

Rule:
- shared/ui must remain feature-agnostic

---

# 4. Feature UI Layer

- business-specific UI composition
- can use shared/ui + primitives
- may contain local UI state

Rule:
- feature UI is composition layer, not foundation layer

---

# 5. Layout Layer

- structural UI composition only
- no business logic
- no reusable domain components

Rule:
- layout defines structure only

---

# 6. UI Leakage Prevention (UI-ONLY RULES)

Forbidden:

- primitives importing application code
- shared/ui importing features UI
- features importing other features UI directly
- layouts importing feature internals directly

Rule:
- UI boundary violations are structural defects

---

# 7. Component Creation Rule

Before creating UI:

1. check primitives (shadcn)
2. check shared/ui
3. check feature existing components
4. then create new component

Rule:
- reuse is mandatory before creation

---

# 8. UI Stability Rule

- primitives and shared/ui are high-stability layers
- feature UI evolves faster than base UI layers

Rule:
- lower UI layers must evolve slower than features

---

# 9. System Guarantee

If respected:

- consistent UI hierarchy across system
- no UI-level coupling between domains
- predictable component composition model
- scalable UI architecture under growth